# Packages in Java

## Introduction

As applications grow larger, managing hundreds or thousands of classes in a single folder becomes difficult.

Imagine a college management system:

```text
Student.java
Teacher.java
Department.java
Attendance.java
Library.java
Book.java
Account.java
Fee.java
```

If all files are stored together, the project becomes difficult to organize.

To solve this problem, Java provides:

```text
Packages
```

Packages help organize related classes and interfaces into separate namespaces.

---

# What is a Package?

A Package is a collection of related classes, interfaces, enums, and sub-packages.

Think of a package like a folder on your computer.

Example:

```text
College Management System

student
    Student.java
    Attendance.java

library
    Book.java
    Library.java

finance
    Account.java
    Fee.java
```

Each folder represents a package.

---

# Why Do We Need Packages?

Packages provide:

- Better Code Organization
- Name Conflict Prevention
- Access Protection
- Easier Maintenance
- Reusability

---

# Real-World Example

Without Packages:

```text
Student.java
Book.java
Employee.java
Teacher.java
Account.java
```

All files in one folder.

Difficult to manage.

---

With Packages:

```text
student.Student
library.Book
employee.Employee
finance.Account
```

Well organized and easy to understand.

---

# Types of Packages

Java supports two types:

## Built-in Packages

Packages already provided by Java.

Examples:

```java
java.util
java.io
java.lang
java.sql
java.time
```

---

## User-Defined Packages

Packages created by programmers.

Example:

```java
student.management
```

```java
college.library
```

```java
com.company.project
```

---

# Package Naming Convention

Packages should always be written in:

```text
lowercase
```

Correct:

```java
student.management
```

```java
college.library
```

```java
com.company.project
```

Wrong:

```java
Student.Management
```

```java
COLLEGE.LIBRARY
```

---

# Creating Your First Package

## Step 1

Create a folder:

```text
student
```

---

## Step 2

Create Student.java

```java
package student;

public class Student {

    public void display() {

        System.out.println(
                "Student Package");
    }
}
```

---

# Understanding

```java
package student;
```

means:

```text
This class belongs to
student package
```

---

# Using a Package Class

Create Main.java

```java
import student.Student;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student s =
                new Student();

        s.display();
    }
}
```

---

# Output

```text
Student Package
```

---

# Package Structure

```text
Project

│

├── Main.java

│

